git init :
Initializing a git repositort, it creates an empty repository which lated can be put on github

git status :
Tells us aobut the status of the repository, like files that got deleted/added/modified

Git can actually allow us to decide what files we want to update or track.
git add file>location file2>location
But we can use git add . --> to select all the files in our directory.


For example when we enter "git status" without actually tracking any of our files this error will occur:

On branch master

// No commits yet
// Untracked files:
//  (use "git add <file>..." to include in what will be committed)
//        Git commands
//        config.js
//        src/

//nothing added to commit but untracked files present (use "git add" to track)

But if we type "git add ." and check with "git status" again:

// On branch master

// No commits yet

// Changes to be committed:
//  (use "git rm --cached <file>..." to unstage)
//        new file:   .prettierignore
//        new file:   Git commands
//        new file:   config.js
//        new file:   src/server.js

Everything is ok, gut we still hadn't commited any of the files yet.

which is done by this command : 'git commit -m "description" '
'-m' means that you want to give a description.



we can also use 'git log' command to get info about who, when had commited.

Also everytime we "git commit" our changes a new version is created, to avoid it we can do this instead:
'git commit -m "Still version 1" --amend'
using the cose '--amend' will make sure that our commit is being sent to the previous version, thanks to it a new version will not be created.
'git lot' will only show commits that created a new version